    {
      "fieldConfig": {
        "defaults": {},
        "overrides": []
      },
      "gridPos": {
        "h": 3,
        "w": 6,
        "x": 0,
        "y": 8
      },
      "id": 10,
      "options": {
        "code": {
          "language": "plaintext",
          "showLineNumbers": false,
          "showMiniMap": false
        },
        "content": "RSRP — Reference Signal Received Power\n\nRaw signal strength from the base station (dBm). Measures how strongly the tower is transmitting to your device.\n\n🟢 > -85 Excellent · 🟡 -85 to -100 OK · 🟠 -100 to -110 Weak · 🔴 < -110 Very weak\n\nLow RSRP is caused by distance to the tower, physical obstructions (buildings, trees), or poor antenna positioning.",
        "mode": "markdown"
      },
      "pluginVersion": "12.4.1",
      "title": "",
      "type": "text"
    },
    {
      "fieldConfig": {
        "defaults": {},
        "overrides": []
      },
      "gridPos": {
        "h": 3,
        "w": 6,
        "x": 6,
        "y": 8
      },
      "id": 11,
      "options": {
        "code": {
          "language": "plaintext",
          "showLineNumbers": false,
          "showMiniMap": false
        },
        "content": "RSRQ — Reference Signal Received Quality\n\nSignal quality relative to interference (dB). Measures how clean the signal is compared to noise from neighbouring towers and interference.\n\n🟢 > -8 Excellent · 🟡 -8 to -10 OK · 🟠 -10 to -15 Poor · 🔴 < -15 Very poor\n\nLow RSRQ despite good RSRP = many active users on the tower, or high interference in the area.",
        "mode": "markdown"
      },
      "pluginVersion": "12.4.1",
      "title": "",
      "type": "text"
    },
    {
      "fieldConfig": {
        "defaults": {},
        "overrides": []
      },
      "gridPos": {
        "h": 3,
        "w": 6,
        "x": 12,
        "y": 8
      },
      "id": 12,
      "options": {
        "code": {
          "language": "plaintext",
          "showLineNumbers": false,
          "showMiniMap": false
        },
        "content": "SINR — Signal to Interference and Noise Ratio\n\nSignal vs noise and interference (dB). The most important metric for actual data throughput — directly determines which modulation scheme the router can use.\n\n🟢 > 20 Excellent · 🟡 10-20 Good · 🟠 0-10 OK · 🔴 < 0 Poor\n\nSINR drops when the tower is under heavy load or when interference is high.",
        "mode": "markdown"
      },
      "pluginVersion": "12.4.1",
      "title": "",
      "type": "text"
    },
    {
      "fieldConfig": {
        "defaults": {},
        "overrides": []
      },
      "gridPos": {
        "h": 3,
        "w": 6,
        "x": 18,
        "y": 8
      },
      "id": 13,
      "options": {
        "code": {
          "language": "plaintext",
          "showLineNumbers": false,
          "showMiniMap": false
        },
        "content": "RSSI — Received Signal Strength Indicator\n\nTotal received signal strength (dBm). Includes all signal — noise and interference from other transmitters included. Less useful on its own.\n\n🟢 > -75 Good · 🟡 -75 to -85 OK · 🟠 -85 to -95 Weak · 🔴 < -95 Very weak\n\nCompare with RSRP: a large gap between RSSI and RSRP indicates high interference levels in the area.",
        "mode": "markdown"
      },
      "pluginVersion": "12.4.1",
      "title": "",
      "type": "text"
    },
